I just couldn't resist coming back for more. While most of the info in this comic was essentially based on fact, it's not entirely accurate... more like the kind of stuff you'd learn by watching a half-hour nature special on Animal Planet. The spiders are very obviously from the genus Argiope (probably Argiope amoena) and, while their biology is generally well-described, their mating behavior is almost entirely fictionalized. Heck, the males in this comic were far larger and look completely different than they do in real life. A real spider of any kind would lack the strength to break a limb with its legs, they just don't work like that, and male palps are not shaped like a penis; they're actually shaped to fit into the female's hardened epigyne like a lock fits a key, which prevents them from mating with a female of the wrong species. In some species of Argiope, the male will plug the female's epigyne with his palps after copulation to prevent another male from mating with her. Fun!
